title: For Sale/Trade:  Remington mod 81 in 300 savage--- not  magnum
postcontent: Remington 81 in 300Savage cartridge. the rifle that interrupted the ongoing legend of the 94 Winchester in 30/30. While both are brush guns, or saddle guns, the 81'bested the 94 in its shrouded insulated barrel that could be put under a saddled horse blanket no problem, and it would shoot semi auto to take down that. Come Upon by chance, Bear or Cat, or maybe an Angry Elk in rut! not only faster but bigger cartridge to absolutely save your life. It was highly sought after when updated from the 1900  model 8. in 1936. This is a 1938 model 81 and she's a rare beauty, from one end to another, bore perfect, action smooth as a baby. This rifle was a legend in the logging and hunting camps of the northern territories and great north West, and along the Canadian borders on both sides before WWII. It was bought by my Granddad in Salem Ore in 1938 and my dad passed it to me. I don't hunt any more, legs gone and Ill have to let her go .  My dad cherished this gun, now he's gone, and its time to move  along. Hope someone will appreciate this old northern legend, and take care of her as we have. Attention this is not a magnum it is a 300 Savage cartridge and I had no option but to select mag as caliber.

title: For Sale:  Remington Model 11 Sportsman
location: Arlington, Granite Falls, Marysville, Everett, Seattle, Washington
postcontent: For sale I have a 1939 Remington Model 11 Sportsman semiautomatic 12 gauge. The shotgun originally had a Poly Choke on the end of the barrel, but one of the fingers of the choke was broken off and barrels are not cheap for this gun. So I cut the choke off before the threads, filed it even and reblued the crown of the barrel, so it is a cylinder bore shotgun now. I already have two other twelve gauges and don't really need this one, so that's why I'm getting rid of it. The gun functions good, cycles and feeds great and recoil isn't bad at all. Crossbolt safety, light trigger and the big barrel bead make it a good setup for anyone. I believe springs have been replaced in action because they're stiff like a new gun. 2+1 setup for hunting so you're good to go for the field. Based on the productions numbers, it looks like the gun was produced between 1939 and early 1940, but the numbers are hard to follow. I've seen shotguns like this in rougher shape go for a lot more. Bluing is in great shape, wood stock is in okay shape, it would be easy to refinish. I can even refinish the stock for a cheap price if you'd prefer.

BN coatings are extremely slick, low friction, high lubricity, abrasion resistant coatings. They also make cleaning easier and add to the heat dissipating properties of your treated parts.You gun or parts will be a matte silver color when done. Because of their low friction and high lubricity, these coatings reduce or eliminate the need for excessive oil use; and reduce the need and increase the time intervals between maintenance. Because the coatings are harder than the substrate over which they are applied, they reduce or eliminate wear and tear.

Nib coatings work well for bolts, carriers, frames, pins, receivers, AR uppers and lowers, slides, hammers, strikers, firing pins, magazines and followers.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Sig Sauer / Browning  BDA  9mm
postcontent:
For sale or possible trade in the Roanoke Valley is a Browning BDA 9mm (made by SIG SAUER in W. Germany) in great condition. It would make a nice addition to your Browning or SIG collection. Apparently these are fairly scarce pistols. It is roll marked on the left side of the slide "Browning Arms Co. Morgan, UT & Montreal P.Q." and on the right side of the slide is the serial number and "SIG-Sauer System Made in W. Germany". It has Browning molded into the right side grip and features a European style heel magazine release also.

The short history as I've read on various sites is that Sig Sauer contracted with Browning to import them as the Browning Double Action or BDA. Browning imported these guns from 1977 to 1980 in fairly small numbers until Sig decided to import to the US on their own. They are basically the predecessor to the P220 series that Sig imported themselves after 1980. The most to least common (SIG) BDA was chambered in .45ACP (used by the Huntington Beach Police Department with much success during that time), then the 9mm (2,740 made), and the least common is the 38 Super (753 made).

This SIG/Browning comes with two magazines and an owners manual.

PRIZE RIFLE: See below for details

HOW DOES IT WORK?

You bring your military surplus rifle (any rifle issued to or used by a military anywhere in the world) this includes anything from a revolutionary war musket to any weapon made pre 1957. If you have a question weather your weapon was issued, please feel free to ask. 

~~~~~Bring YOUR Military surplus rifle and ammo. 5 shots, 100 yards, open sights. Bi pods and rests are now allowed. (No full sleds, you have to hold the rifle yourself). The top score takes home the prize rifle. It's that simple.

Tickets are $20 each, 3 for $50. You can enter as many times as you like. You can pre pay via pay pal or pay cash at the time of the shoot.

Rather than going 1 shooter at a time like last year, we will be going at it with banks of 4 shooters per round. This will speed everything up quite a bit. A pair of complaints from last year was it took so long to cycle everyone through the same rifle and going in cold with an unfamiliar weapon just kind of sucked. SO, going this route. knowing your own weapon, and a bank of shooters will more than likely ramp up the speed and excitement of the events.

A spotter will still be provided. If you have a spotting scope, please bring it with you, we can not have enough of them there. 

Our faithful Range master will score the target. His word is the final say in any disputes over whatever may come up. There has never been a problem to date with score disputes, but I just wanted to put that out there for the record. 

Also, bring camp chairs or something to sit on. As always I'll bring the water for everyone & am working with a couple of people to sponsor/provide hot food as well, but that's not guaranteed yet. It's still in the works. If you are a food vendor/restaurant owner and want to talk sponsorship, please message me.

That's about it for the Milsurp portion of the shoot.

Questions? Message or call me. My contact info is below.

_______________________________________________________

The next event held immediately after the Milsurp Shoot is what we call Run What'cha Brung. 

This is open to any and all rifles, any caliber, milsurp or not. Scoped or not at your preference. Bi pods and rests are also welcome. The same rules apply as above. 5 shots, but this one is out to 200 yards, top score takes home 1/2 of the entry fees. 

Slots are $10 each. In the event of a tie, the target will be moved out to 300 yards. In the event of another tie we'll do what we did at the November 2013 shoot. 5 16 oz water bottles set up at 300 yards-5 shots, whoever takes the most out wins. It's that simple.

After both events there will be open range time for everyone to shoot and have fun. There are pistol pits as well as the 300 yard range. Bring your big kid toys & lets have a great day!

_______________________________________________________

PLEASE FEEL FREE TO BRING ANY TRADE/SALE GOODS YOU MAY WANT TO MOVE ALONG TO A NEW HOME. 

Bring anything you like that is related to shooting/hunting, survival/personal defense and the like along. I'm sure someone will be interested. I would like to see this portion build up to a full scale trade/barter show some day sp lets get out there and do some tradin'!

'Odd' calibers like 7.7 Jap 7.5x55 Swiss and similar are always in demand. As are more common calibers like 7/8mm mauser, 30/30, 30-06, .45 in all flavors, 9mm ...you get the idea. 

If it's legal, bring it out. 
_______________________________________________________

This is a casual and relaxed shoot, so please no 'rules lawyers' or nit pickers. This is for fun more than anything else. Relax & have a good time. Safety, however is paramount.

Eye and Ear protection are mandatory and are non negotiable. If you refuse to wear them, you will be asked to leave. Again, it's that simple. We generally have spare foamy ear plugs for those who forget theirs and an extra pair of glasses or 2 just in case.

This is a family event and we encourage you to bring them along, we love kids & everyone needs a personal cheering section..lol 

Every so often we will mix things up a little and add an extra event like a poker shoot, bowling pin shoot, shotgun/skeet/trap and whatever else we can think of. If you have any thoughts, comments or suggestions please message me or comment on the pinned post on the primary shoot off page.

DIRECTIONS:

Off of Hwy 54, Take Hwy A/ A rd to Garrison, (approx. 4 1/2 miles from 54), make a right. (Garrison is just across the road from the MO Trap Shooters Assn.) Down Garrison hill. across the low water bridge, 75 yards up on the right you will see the range. Come on in and introduce yourself to the group & have fun. 

My phone number is 573 286 4 zero 9 zero if you get lost or need any more information. 

PRIZE RIFLE: The first place prize rifle will change every month, It depends on what I find and what the group decides they want. Last year it was Mosins and Mausers. I will do my very best to find a variety of quality rifles to keep it fresh and interesting. The first prize of the year will be a Mosin Nagant 7.62x54R. I have set up a group buy for a crate of Mosins and get the first selection. The best rifle from that crate will be the prize at our first shoot. The crate has not yet arrived so I do not know what exactly it is yet, I will update this post after it lands here.

I hope to see you there.

You can find us on Facebook by searching Linn Creek Milsurp Shoot Off.

We have pics of past shoots and a great bunch of folk having fun on the group page. Drop in and say howdy.

title: For Sale:  Beautiful1873 Winchester Rifle .32 man
postcontent: Up for sale is a Winchester model 1873, according to multiple sources the serial number 624***B was produced in 1909-1910. All records from 1907-1961 were destroyed in a fire at the Winchester Headquarters in 1961 so This is as accurate a time frame as can be given. Gun is complete and would be rated as above average condition based on patina, lack of repairs and general condition of wood and metal (Little original bluing is left, little to no pitting in metal, most corners are still crisp and present, wood is original walnut base model with no noticable damage/splits/rot and all original parts are present and in working order) Barrel length measures 26" (from muzzle to face of closed action using a wooden dowel down the inside of the barrel) this indicates the barrel is a custom length from the standard 24" barrel. Barrel is full octagonal, bright and shiny inside, rifling looks superb. All model 1873 made after serial # 525923 are NOT considered antique, hence any purchaser will have to use a liscened FFL receiver to ship to (if you aren't sure how this works, ask me) Rifle uses 32 WCF ammunition.buyer pays for all shipping costs.

The .300 H&H Magnum Cartridge was introduced by the British company Holland & Holland as the Super-Thirty in June, 1925.
